            {
                "s2_paper_id": "5e097ef7b0e4326ad93898f6bbb5b2b3e4713b29",
                "title": "Oral cavity masses in a newborn",
                "year": 2021,
                "venue": "Archives of Disease in Childhood",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 6,
                "abstract": "A term healthy female baby born via normal vaginal delivery was referred to us for oral cavity masses noticed soon after birth. On examination, there were two pedunculated red round masses attached to hard palate near the gingiva with no other associated anomalies (figure 1). All antenatal scans of the mother were normal. Based on the clinical examination, diagnosis of congenital epulis (CE) was made and the patient was scheduled for surgical correction. Excision of the masses followed by cauterisation of the peduncles was done under general anaesthesia. Postoperatively, diagnosis was confirmed by histological exam (H&E stain) of the tissue with the presence of tumour cells having abundant granular eosinophilic cytoplasm suggestive of CE (figure 2). The baby was discharged on postoperative day 2. CE is a rare benign lesion noticed normally after birth as a solitary lesion but multiple masses can also be seen. It presents as normal to reddishcoloured sessile or pedunculated mass in variable size having smooth surface protruding from the oral cavity. 2 It may interfere with breast feeding and rarely with the respiration. It occurs more often in girls than boys. It is mainly seen in the maxillary alveolar process area, lateral to the midline. Aetiology of CE is unknown. There are usually no associated dental or other congenital malformations. Differential diagnosis for oral masses includes teratoma, haemangioma, fibroma, rhabdomyoma and CE. The treatment of choice is surgical excision either under general anaesthesia or local anaesthesia for small lesions. Histological examination showing granular cells is the gold standard for diagnosis. Longterm prognosis is good after surgery.",
